INTRODUCTION

With the goal of predicting hourly electricity consumption in Turkey a time series analysis is conducted and autoregressive (AR) and moving-average (MA) models are applied.

Data used is a publicly available data provided by EP襤A.Downloaded as a .csv file from the website of EP襤A.

Data initially has 3 columns and 47208 observations. The columns are Date, Hour and Consumption..MWh.. Date and Hour columns are combined into a DateTime column in a form of a datetime object. Consumption..MWh. changed as Consumpt

library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)
library(lubridate)
library(urca)
library(forecast)
setwd("C://Users//P覺nar YILDIRIM//Desktop//IE360")
consumption=read.csv("RealTimeConsumption-01012016-20052021.csv")
consumption = as.data.table(consumption)

setnames(consumption, "Consumption..MWh.", "Consumpt")
consumption$Consumpt=gsub("\\.", "", (consumption$Consumpt))
consumption$Consumpt=gsub("\\,", ".", (consumption$Consumpt))
consumption$Consumpt=as.numeric(consumption$Consumpt)
consumption$Date=as.Date(consumption$Date, format="%d.%m.%Y")
consumption$DateTime = paste(consumption$Date,consumption$Hour)
consumption$DateTime = as_datetime(consumption$DateTime, format="%Y-%m-%d %H:%M")

summary(consumption)

VISUALIZING THE DATA

(ggplot(data=consumption, aes(x=DateTime,y=Consumpt))+geom_line()
  +labs(x="Date",y="Consumption (MWh)",title="Hourly Consumption")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14)
)

Hourly consumption data shows seasonality. Monthly seasonality could be observed from the graph. In summer months consumption is higher. It is also high in winter months but not as high as it is in the summer. Two spikes during summer months correspond the religious holidays. That one spike corresponds to the lowest consumption value which is 0 on 27 March 2016. This may be due to a mistake in measurements since there is not a significant event on that day. During the lockdown period due to COVID-19 in 2020 there is a significant decrease in electricity consumption.

Lets take a closer look.

(ggplot(data=consumption[consumption$Date>="2017-01-01"&consumption$Date<="2020-01-01"], aes(x=DateTime,y=Consumpt))+geom_line()
  +labs(x="Date",y="Consumption (MWh)",title="Hourly Consumption for 3 Years ")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14)
)

Yearly seasonality is observed more clearly with effects of each month visible in the three-years window above.

(ggplot(data=consumption[consumption$Date>="2017-02-01"&consumption$Date<="2017-03-01"], aes(x=DateTime,y=Consumpt))+geom_line()
  +labs(x="Date",y="Consumption (MWh)",title="Hourly Consumption for 1 Month")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14)
)

To observe weekly seasonality we have the plot for a month where the effect of each week day is observable.

(ggplot(data=consumption[consumption$Date>="2017-02-01"&consumption$Date<="2017-02-03"], aes(x=DateTime,y=Consumpt))+geom_line()
  +labs(x="Date",y="Consumption (MWh)",title="Hourly Consumption for 3 Days ")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14)
)

Finally, there is the consumption plot for 3 days. Where the hourly patterns are clearly visible.

Three types of seasonality, which are daily, weekly and yearly, are observed. To account for these seasonality components data will be decomposed.

DECOMPOSITION

First, lets check seasonality on a daily level.

#daily
consumption_daily=ts(consumption$Consumpt,frequency = 24)
daily_decompose=decompose(consumption_daily)
plot(daily_decompose)

In the seasonal part seasonality is tried to be explained daily and in the trend part we have the trend component.Seasonal component is hard to visibly understand since each hour has a effect.Trend component has a seasonality itself.

Lets check weekly seasonality and effect of each day on data.

#weekly
consumption_weekly=ts(consumption$Consumpt,frequency = 24*7)
weekly_decompose=decompose(consumption_weekly)
plot(weekly_decompose)

In the seasonal part seasonality is tried to be explained weekly and in the trend part we have the trend component.Seasonal component is more distinguished but still hard to visibly interpret. Trend component still has seasonality.

#yearly
consumption_yearly=ts(consumption$Consumpt,frequency = 24*360)
yearly_decompose=decompose(consumption_yearly)
plot(yearly_decompose)

In this plot there is the seasonality is tried to be explained yearly. Trend component does not have a seasonality anymore.

DECOMPOSING THE SERIES (FREQUENCY = 24*7)

Additive decomposition with frequency = 24*7

consumption_ts=ts(consumption$Consumpt,frequency = 24*7)
consumption_ts_decomp=decompose(consumption_ts,type="additive")
plot(consumption_ts_decomp)

To have better plots:

consumption$additive_trend=consumption_ts_decomp$trend
(ggplot(data=consumption, aes(x=DateTime,y=additive_trend))+geom_line()
  +labs(x="Date",y="Trend Cycle",title="Trend Cycle Component")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14)
)

consumption$additive_seasonal=consumption_ts_decomp$seasonal
(ggplot(data=consumption, aes(x=DateTime,y=additive_seasonal))+geom_line()
  +labs(x="Date",y="Seasonality",title="Seasonal Component")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14)
)

Seasonality still not clear. We can observe it on a 1-month time window as such

(ggplot(data=consumption[consumption$Date>="2017-02-01"&consumption$Date<="2017-03-01"], aes(x=DateTime,y=additive_seasonal))+geom_line()
  +labs(x="Date",y="Seasonality",title="Seasonal Component")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14)
)

We have the seasonality component which accounts for the effect of each hour and each day.

Comparison of Multiplicative and Additive decomposition

plot(consumption_ts_decomp_m)

plot(consumption_ts_decomp)

In both methods trend has some seasonality still. Random component has a non-zero mean in multiplicative decomposition but has a zero mean in additive decomposition. Variance of the random term is in a range in both methods. Not to violate 0 mean assumption additive decomposition will be used.

AR MODEL

When the consumption data is deseasonalized and de trended, random term is left.

consumption$random=consumption_ts_decomp$random
(ggplot(data=consumption, aes(x=DateTime,y=random))+geom_line()
  +labs(x="Date",y="Random Consumption",title="Random Component")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14)
)

Firts check if the random term is stationary or not with KPSS test.

test1=ur.kpss(consumption$random) 
summary(test1)
## 
## ####################### 
## # KPSS Unit Root Test # 
## ####################### 
## 
## Test is of type: mu with 18 lags. 
## 
## Value of test-statistic is: 0.0042 
## 
## Critical value for a significance level of: 
##                 10pct  5pct 2.5pct  1pct
## critical values 0.347 0.463  0.574 0.739

Since the test-statistic 0.0042 is smaller than even 10pct (0.347) random component is stationary.

Check ACF and PACF functions

acf(consumption[complete.cases(consumption)]$random)

pacf(consumption[complete.cases(consumption)]$random)

ACF is sinusoidal and there is a significant spike at lag 0.15 in the PACF but none beyond. Both suggest that ARIMA(p,d,0) should be used.

Different values for (p) parameter are checked.

aic=list()
for(i in 0:5){
    aic[i] = AIC(arima(consumption$random, order=c(i,0,0)))
}
print(aic)

train_set=ts(consumption[DateTime<"2021-05-06"]$random)
model=arima(train_set, order=c(2,0,5))

test_set=consumption[DateTime>"2021-05-06",]


forecasted=forecast(model,h=362)


str(test_set)

test_set$forecasts=forecasted$mean
test_set[,prediction:=forecasts+as.numeric(additive_trend)+as.numeric(additive_seasonal)]

(ggplot(data=test_set, aes(x=DateTime, y=Consumpt))+geom_line(aes(color="consumption"))
  +geom_line(aes(y=prediction,color="prediction"))
  +labs(x="Date",y="Consumption",title="Forecasts vs Actual")
  +theme_minimal(base_size=14))

Mean absolute percentage errors by day

test_set[,error:=abs(Consumpt-prediction)]
test_set[,perc_error:=error/Consumpt]
test_set[,mean_byday:=mean(perc_error),by=Date]

days=(unique(test_set$Date))
errors=test_set[,mean(mean_byday),by=Date]
print(cbind(days,errors))
